The command line tool cocos does not respect productFlavors from build.gradle. I've added

```
android {
    productFlavors {
        amazon {}
        google {}
    }
}
```

and after that, the APK is named **product-flavor-debug.apk**, but this isn't moved to bin/debug/android. Instead it crashes, because it did not find any **product-debug.apk**.

The best way to do it, is to change the command **cocos compile** command to do a **gradlew clean** to delete all old data and after a **gradlew build** (can be combined to **gradlew clean build**) cocos could copy all **product-*-debug.apk** into the bin/debug/android. Same problem is with **-m release**. The **clean** does not delete any cocos2d-libs, if they are compile from source.

PS: The **cocos deploy** should receive a new arg like **-f flavor**.
